  "prompt": "What is a polite way to address someone in email whose gender you don't know?",
  "response": "Here are several polite ways to address someone in an email when you don't know their gender:\n\n**General & Safe Options:**\n\n*   **\"To Whom It May Concern:\"** This is a classic and formal option. While some find it outdated, it's still perfectly acceptable and respectful, especially in formal or professional contexts.\n*   **\"Dear Sir/Madam:\"** Similar to \"To Whom It May Concern,\" this is a traditional formal option. Use it with the same considerations as above.\n*   **\"Dear [Full Name]:\"**  If you know the person's full name, this is a great option. It's professional and personalized.\n    *   Example: \"Dear Jane Doe:\"\n*   **\"Dear [Job Title]:\"** If you know their job title, this is a good way to address them.\n    *   Example: \"Dear Hiring Manager:\" or \"Dear Customer Service Representative:\"\n*   **\"Hello [Full Name]:\"**  A slightly more casual, but still professional, option using their full name.\n*   **\"Good morning/afternoon [Full Name]:\"** A friendly and professional greeting combined with their full name.\n\n**Modern & Preferred Options (Often Considered Best):**\n\n*   **Omit the Salutation Entirely:**  Instead of a salutation, simply start directly with the body of your email.  This is becoming increasingly common, especially in less formal settings.\n    *   **Example:**\n        *   Subject: Inquiry about [Subject]\n        *   I am writing to inquire about...\n*   **\"Hello\":** A simple and universally accepted greeting. If you want to be more formal, you can combine it with their last name, if known.\n    *   Example: \"Hello\" or \"Hello Ms./Mr. Doe\" (if you are okay using this without knowing gender)\n* **\"Greetings\":** Another very general and neutral option that works well.\n\n**Things to Avoid:**\n\n*   **\"Dear Sir or Madam\" (or variations):** This is outdated and can sound impersonal.\n*   **Making Assumptions:** Avoid using gendered pronouns (he/she, him/her) until you know the person's preferred pronouns. If you need to refer to them before knowing, you can rephrase the sentence or use \"they/them\" in the singular.\n*   **Informal Greetings (if inappropriate):** Avoid very casual greetings like \"Hey\" or \"Hi\" unless you know the person or the context is very informal.\n\n**Choosing the Best Option:**\n\nConsider the following when choosing:\n\n*   **Formality of the situation:** A formal application or request requires a more formal salutation than a quick inquiry to a company's customer service department.\n*   **Your relationship with the recipient:** If you've communicated with them before (even without knowing their gender), a more casual option might be appropriate.\n*   **Company/Organizational Culture:** If you're familiar with the company's culture, you can tailor your salutation to match.\n\n**In summary, the safest and often preferred options are to use their full name if you know it, omit the salutation entirely, or use a general greeting like \"Hello\" or \"Greetings.\"**  If you're unsure, err on the side of formality.\n",
